{
  "answer": "In Cynewulf's *Andreas*, Andrew (Andreas) encounters Christ disguised as the helmsman on a divinely guided ship. A representative \"speech-back\" moment occurs when Andrew praises the helmsman's supernatural skill at sea and humbly requests to learn his secret, probing the divine figure's wisdom despite the apparent power imbalance of a mere apostle addressing the Savior.[^1]\n\nIn *Elene*, Helena (Elene) confronts the Jewish elders and wise men, demanding they reveal the True Cross based on prophetic lore they claim to know. She rebukes them sharply for rejecting Christ despite scriptural signs from Moses, David, and Isaiah, asserting her imperial authority over their scholarly evasion.[^2]\n\nIn *Juliana*, the saint rejects her pagan suitor Eleusius (Heliseus), the local prefect, insisting he convert or forfeit her: \"You will never compel me with your commands, / nor prepare so many cruel punishments / that I should love your lordship, unless you forsake / those falsehoods, your idol-worship...\" Later, alone in prison, she interrogates and rebukes a demon disguised as an angel, binding it and forcing confession of its evils: \"You must tell me further, / fiend of mankind, of your journey, / and who sent you to me.\"[^3]\n\nThese moments highlight inverted power dynamics: apostle to incarnate God; empress to scholars; martyr to tormentor and devil. Which saint—Andrew, Helena, or Juliana—pays the highest price for such bold speech in the face of these relations?\n\n[^1]: Cynewulf, *Andreas*, [paragraph](/works/cynewulf-andreas-07b573/01/translation/#p-ca9772).\n\n[^2]: Cynewulf, *Elene*, [paragraph](/works/cynewulf-elene-d2d132/01/translation/#p-f5d1f1).\n\n[^3]: Cynewulf, *Juliana*, [paragraphs](/works/cynewulf-juliana-9a2157/01/translation/#p-6a2534) (to Eleusius); [paragraph](/works/cynewulf-juliana-9a2157/01/translation/#p-bd327c) (to demon).",
